<header class="header">
  <h1>Short-Season Melon Varieties</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Choose melons that can flower, size fruit, and ripen during your real summer window.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Short-season melons are usually smaller-fruited, earlier varieties that have a better chance of ripening before cool nights and fall frost return.</strong>
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
  <p>
    For short summers, choose melon varieties with early maturity, smaller fruit, and a realistic ripening window after transplanting or direct sowing. Large, long-season melons are much riskier where summer heat is limited.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Safest choices:</strong> compact, early, smaller-fruited melons</li>
    <li><strong>Higher risk:</strong> large melons that need a long hot season</li>
    <li><strong>Main challenge:</strong> melons need both time and heat to ripen well</li>
    <li><strong>Best strategy:</strong> use transplants where appropriate and protect early growth from cold</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What Makes a Melon Short-Season Friendly?</h2>
  <p>
    Melons are warm-season crops, so maturity days alone do not tell the whole story. A melon needs warm soil, steady summer heat, pollination, fruit sizing, and enough time for flavor to develop before frost.
  </p>
  <p>
    Smaller melons generally carry less risk because the plant has less fruit mass to mature. Compact varieties can also be easier to manage with plastic mulch, row cover, or other season-extension tactics.
  </p>
  <ul class="tight">
    <li><strong>Smaller fruit:</strong> usually easier to finish in short summers.</li>
    <li><strong>Early maturity:</strong> reduces the chance of underripe fruit at frost.</li>
    <li><strong>Reliable fruit set:</strong> important when warm pollination weather is limited.</li>
    <li><strong>Strong early growth:</strong> cold starts can delay the entire crop.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

