</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Fruit Size Matters</h2>
  <p>
    In a short season, fruit size is a practical maturity factor. A plant that sets one or two smaller melons may finish them more reliably than a plant trying to mature large fruit late in the summer.
  </p>
  <p>
    Smaller does not guarantee success, but it usually improves your margin when warm days are limited.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Short-Season Melons</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Planting into cold soil:</strong> melons can stall badly when conditions are too cool.</li>
    <li><strong>Choosing large-fruited varieties:</strong> big fruit often needs a longer warm finish.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring nighttime temperatures:</strong> cool nights slow growth even without frost.</li>
    <li><strong>Starting too late:</strong> delayed planting can leave fruit underripe at frost.</li>
    <li><strong>Overplanting long vines:</strong> crowded plants may set late or mature poorly.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Best Strategy for Short Summers</h2>
  <p>
    Choose one early, smaller-fruited melon as the dependable option before experimenting with larger or later varieties. In cold climates, focus on warming the soil, protecting young plants, and avoiding late starts.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Plan Around Your Local Season</h2>
  <p>
    Melons need more than frost-free days. They need a warm enough season to grow strongly and finish fruit. Check both your frost window and your expected seasonal heat before choosing a variety.
  </p>
